<div class=3D"editContent" data-selector=3D".editContent"><h2 class=3D"tbs-=
heading-divider">Kids Bike Size Chart</h2><p>As we stated above, kids bikes=
 are measured by the size of their wheels, and it=E2=80=99s much more strai=
ghtforward than adult sizing. A 12-inch bike has 12-inch wheels, a 16-inch =
bike has 16-inch wheels, and so on. Here is a great general kids bike size =
chart to get started, but <strong>it=E2=80=99s always best to have your chi=
ld try a bike before you buy it.</strong></p><div class=3D"tbs-btn-group le=
ft"><a class=3D"btn btn-primary" href=3D"https://www.thebikeshoppe.com/prod=
uct-list/bikes-1000/kids-bikes-1023/12-inch-1024">12" Bikes</a> <a class=3D=
"btn btn-primary" href=3D"https://www.thebikeshoppe.com/product-list/bikes-=
1000/kids-bikes-1023/16-inch-1026">16" Bikes</a> <a class=3D"btn btn-primar=
y" href=3D"https://www.thebikeshoppe.com/product-list/bikes-1000/kids-bikes=
-1023/20-inch-1028">20" Bikes</a> <a class=3D"btn btn-primary" href=3D"http=
s://www.thebikeshoppe.com/product-list/bikes-1000/kids-bikes-1023/24-inch-1=
029">24" Bikes</a> <a class=3D"btn btn-primary" href=3D"https://www.thebike=
shoppe.com/product-list/bikes-1000/mountain-1006/26-inch-1251">26" Bikes</a=
></div><div style=3D"overflow-x: scroll; margin-top: 30px;"><table class=3D=
"table table-bordered"><thead><tr><th style=3D"text-align: center;">Size</t=
h><th><div style=3D"text-align: center;">Height</div></th><th><div style=3D=
"text-align: center;">Typical* Age</div></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>12=
" wheel</td><td>86.0 - 102.0 cm <br>2'9.9" - 3'4.2"</td><td>2 - 4</td></tr>=
<tr><td>16" wheel</td><td>99.0 - 117.0 cm <br>3'3.0" - 3'10.1"</td><td>4 - =
6</td></tr><tr><td>20" wheel</td><td>114.0 - 132.0 cm <br>3'8.9" - 4'4.0"</=
td><td>6 - 8</td></tr><tr><td>24" wheel</td><td>130.0 - 150.0 cm <br>4'3.2"=
 - 4'11.1"</td><td>8 - 12</td></tr><tr><td>26" wheel</td><td>146.0 - 160.0 =
cm <br>4'9.5" - 5'3.0"</td><td>12 +</td></tr></tbody></table></div><hr styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 6px;"><details><summary>What to do if your child is in =
between kids bike sizes</summary> <p><strong>Go for the larger size if:</st=
rong></p><ul><li>they feel confident on the bigger size</li><li>they're get=
ting into racing or biking as a sport</li></ul><p><strong>Go for the smalle=
r size if:</strong></p><ul><li>they're less confident riders</li></ul><p>It=
's almost always better to size up with kids bikes, but only if they can ac=
tually handle the larger size. Kids grow up fast, and as a parent you'll wa=
nt to try to give them a bike that they can ride for at least a few years, =
not just one.</p><p>There are some exceptions, though. Go too big and they =
may not be able to control the bike, which is more dangerous and certainly =
less fun. Kids will become better riders when they're riding a bike they fe=
el confident on.</p></details></div>
