<div class=3D"editContent" data-selector=3D".editContent"><div class=3D"con=
tent-block-content" id=3D"proper-bike-fit"><h2 class=3D"tbs-heading-divider=
">How to check if a bike is the right size</h2><p>Let=E2=80=99s say you=E2=
=80=99re standing in front of a bike that you=E2=80=99re interested in buyi=
ng and you even know what size bike it is. According to all the size charts=
, the bike should be about right, but how do you know for sure? And what if=
 you=E2=80=99re right on the line between two sizes? Read on to learn some =
of the most important things to consider when looking for the perfect fit.<=
/p><p><strong>Important:&nbsp;</strong>getting the right fit on a bike is j=
ust as important as choosing the right size frame. If you're feeling unsure=
 or experience pain when you ride, you should consider brining your bike to=
 a shop. The Bike Shoppe can help! <a href=3D"https://www.thebikeshoppe.com=
/about/bike-fitting-pg1253.htm">Explore our bike fitting services</a>.</p><=
hr style=3D"margin-bottom: 6px;"><details><summary>Standover Height</summar=
y> <p>Standover height is essentially the distance between the top tube and=
 the ground at the point where you stand over the bar. This is an important=
 measurement to get right because you=E2=80=99ll want some space between yo=
ur groin and the bar when you hop off the seat. For most bikes you=E2=80=99=
ll want an inch or more of standover room for a super comfortable fit. You =
can easily test this by pulling the bike up until it touches your body when=
 you=E2=80=99re standing. If you can pull the wheels up an inch or more, yo=
u should have plenty of space.</p></details><details><summary>Leg Extension=
</summary> <p>After you=E2=80=99ve made sure you have enough standover room=
, you=E2=80=99ll want to make sure your legs have the proper amount of exte=
nsion. You can adjust the seat height to get the right fit, but if you=E2=
=80=99ve jacked the seatpost up to the max and your legs are still very ben=
t when you pedal, you might need a bigger size.</p><p><strong>Here=E2=80=99=
s how to get proper leg extension:</strong></p><p>On the downstroke, or whe=
n the pedal is closest to the ground, you should look to have around a 15-2=
0=C2=B0 bend in your knee. Depending on the person you may prefer more or l=
ess bend, but you want to avoid having your knees come up too high when you=
 pedal, which is uncomfortable, inefficient, and bad for your joints.</p><p=
>Another way to check your leg extension is to put your foot on the pedal a=
nd see if you can lower your heel below the axle of the pedal on the downst=
roke. If you can push your heel a little further than the axle, that=E2=80=
=99s often an optimum position in terms of efficiency and comfort.</p></det=
ails><details><summary>Reach</summary> <p>Reach is pretty much what it soun=
ds like. Specifically, the official reach measurement is usually the horizo=
ntal distance between the bottom bracket and the head tube. More generally,=
 it translates to how far you have to reach to grab the handlebars.</p><p>R=
each is something to consider mostly when you=E2=80=99re an experienced rid=
er and you=E2=80=99re in between two sizes. Selecting a bike with a longer =
reach will feel =E2=80=9Croomier=E2=80=9D, more stable at speed, and genera=
lly more confident on technical terrain. A shorter reach will help the bike=
 feel more responsive, but depending on what kind of riding you do, that ma=
y or may not be what you=E2=80=99re after.</p></details></div></div>
</div>
<div class=3D"col-xs-12 col-lg-6 content-block-column col-margin-bottom" da=
ta-selector=3D"div.content-block-column">
<div class=3D"editContent" data-selector=3D".editContent"><div class=3D"con=
tent-block-content" id=3D"bike-size-faqs"><h2 class=3D"tbs-heading-divider"=
>Bike sizing FAQs</h2><hr style=3D"margin-bottom: 6px;"><details><summary>W=
hat size bicycle is right for my height?</summary> <p>Before you think abou=
t what size bike you are, you=E2=80=99ll want to decide what kind of bike y=
ou want. As we state in the article above, road bikes and mountain bikes of=
ten use a different sizing system, so figure out what style you=E2=80=99re =
looking for first, then consult the charts above.</p><div class=3D"tbs-btn-=
group left"><a class=3D"btn btn-primary" href=3D"https://www.thebikeshoppe.=
com/articles/bike-size-guide-pg1486.htm?srsltid=3DAfmBOoq8AJgWXP0FHzVeenGFc=
lg_-5KxejWbQa4mOsoNufRzaTEyYYri#road-bike-size-chart">Road bike size chart<=
/a> <a class=3D"btn btn-primary" href=3D"https://www.thebikeshoppe.com/arti=
cles/bike-size-guide-pg1486.htm?srsltid=3DAfmBOoq8AJgWXP0FHzVeenGFclg_-5Kxe=
jWbQa4mOsoNufRzaTEyYYri#mountain-bike-size-chart">Mountain Bike size chart<=
/a> <a class=3D"btn btn-primary" href=3D"https://www.thebikeshoppe.com/arti=
cles/bike-size-guide-pg1486.htm?srsltid=3DAfmBOoq8AJgWXP0FHzVeenGFclg_-5Kxe=
jWbQa4mOsoNufRzaTEyYYri#hybrid-bike-size-chart">Hybrid Bike size chart</a><=
/div></details><details><summary>Should your feet touch the ground on a bik=
e?</summary> <p>Ideally you should be able to touch your toes to the ground=
 when sitting on the seat, but if you can put your feet flat on the ground =
it often means that your seat height is too low. If your seat is too low, y=
our knees will be overly bent when pedaling and that can cause discomfort a=
nd joint pain, not to mention it=E2=80=99s not a very efficient way to ride=
.</p><p>If you feel more comfortable with your feet flat on the ground, che=
ck out Electra bikes. They use something called Flat Foot Technology which =
is a frame design where the pedals are moved forward on the frame so you ca=
n get proper leg extension while pedaling but still put your feet flat on t=
he ground when you want to.</p><div><a class=3D"btn btn-primary" href=3D"ht=
tps://www.thebikeshoppe.com/product-list/electra-pg1216/">Shop Electra Bike=
s</a></div></details><details><summary>Should your legs be straight when ri=
ding a bike?</summary> <p>You don=E2=80=99t want your leg to be totally str=
aight on the down stroke, but you don=E2=80=99t want it overly bent either.=
 As we state in the article above, try to get a 15-20=C2=B0 bend in your kn=
ee on the down stroke, or position your seat so your heel can reach below t=
he pedal axle. This is all subjective, the most important thing is to find =
what works for you.</p></details><details><summary>How much does a bike fit=
ting cost?</summary> <p>A professional bike fitting is more exact and thoro=
ugh than a bike shop employee giving you some quick advice. At The Bike Sho=
ppe we offer professional bike fitting services so you can get the most com=
fort and performance out of your ride. We offer fittings for recreational r=
iders, as well as racers and triathletes.</p><div><a class=3D"btn btn-prima=
ry" href=3D"https://www.thebikeshoppe.com/about/bike-fitting-services-pg125=
3.htm">Explore Bike Fitting Packages</a></div></details><details><summary>D=
o I need a 26 or 29 bike?</summary> <p>26-inch wheels were the mountain bik=
e standard in the past, but most mid and upper tier mountain bikes you=E2=
=80=99ll see on the market today use either 29-inch wheels or the slightly =
smaller 27.5-inch wheels. 29ers and 27.5+ bikes have faster top speeds and =
roll over obstacles easier than 26-inch wheels, so if you want to ride off-=
road, you=E2=80=99ll appreciate bigger tires. 26-inch wheels are often grea=
t for kids who have graduated from their 24-inch kids bike but aren=E2=80=
=99t quite big enough to use the bigger wheels found on most adult bikes.</=
p><div class=3D"tbs-btn-group left"><a class=3D"btn btn-primary" href=3D"ht=
tps://www.thebikeshoppe.com/product-list/bikes-1000/mountain-1006/26-inch-1=
251">Shop 26 inch mountain bikes</a> <a class=3D"btn btn-primary" href=3D"h=
ttps://www.thebikeshoppe.com/product-list/bikes-1000/mountain-1006/650b-123=
1">Shop 27.5 inch mountain bikes</a> <a class=3D"btn btn-primary" href=3D"h=
ttps://www.thebikeshoppe.com/product-list/bikes-1000/29-inch-wheel-29ers-10=
09/">Shop 29 inch mountain bikes</a></div></details><details><summary>What =
size bike does a ____ year old need?</summary> <p>Kids bike sizing is more =
about height, inseam, and confidence than age. One 8 year old might ride a =
different size bike than another 8 year old. Because kids grow at different=
 rates, the absolute best way to get the right size kids bike is by having =
them try it out. But certainly check out the size chart above so you can ge=
t a good idea of where they might be.</p><div class=3D"tbs-btn-group left">=
<a class=3D"btn btn-primary" href=3D"https://www.thebikeshoppe.com/product-=
list/bikes-1000/kids-bikes-1023/12-inch-1024">Shop 12 inch kids bikes</a> <=
a class=3D"btn btn-primary" href=3D"https://www.thebikeshoppe.com/product-l=
ist/bikes-1000/kids-bikes-1023/16-inch-1026">Shop 16 inch kids bikes</a> <a=
 class=3D"btn btn-primary" href=3D"https://www.thebikeshoppe.com/product-li=
st/bikes-1000/kids-bikes-1023/20-inch-1028">Shop 20 inch kids bikes</a> <a =
class=3D"btn btn-primary" href=3D"https://www.thebikeshoppe.com/product-lis=
t/bikes-1000/kids-bikes-1023/24-inch-1029">Shop 24 inch kids bikes</a> <a c=
lass=3D"btn btn-primary" href=3D"https://www.thebikeshoppe.com/product-list=
/bikes-1000/mountain-1006/26-inch-1251">Shop 26 inch Bikes</a></div></detai=
ls><details><summary>What size is a 26 inch bike?</summary> <p>The 26 in a =
26 inch bike refers to the wheel size, so that measurement isn=E2=80=99t al=
ways the best way to judge how big a bike is. Some youth bikes are measured=
 by this wheel size, but more commonly you=E2=80=99ll find 26-inch wheels o=
n a variety of adult frame sizes.</p><div><a class=3D"btn btn-primary" href=
=3D"https://www.thebikeshoppe.com/product-list/bikes-1000/mountain-1006/26-=
inch-1251">Shop 26-inch bikes</a></div></details><details><summary>Is a 26 =
inch bike for adults?</summary> <p>In short, yes! 26-inch wheels are used o=
n adult bikes and have been for years. That being said, most modern mountai=
n bikes have switched to 27.5=E2=80=9D and 29=E2=80=9D inch wheels for thei=
r superior speed, traction, and rollover power. However, 26 inch wheels are=
 super strong and universally available, so bike tourers often use them for=
 traveling abroad.</p></details><details><summary>Can I rent a bike to see =
if it fits?</summary> <p>Absolutely, we offer bike rentals for adult bikes =
and you can try out certain models to make sure you get the right bike for =
you. Head over to our <a href=3D"https://www.thebikeshoppe.com/products/bik=
e-rentals-pg1315.htm">bike rentals</a> page for more info.</p></details></d=
iv></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
